            . I <rs id="t18300527-170-viclabel918" type="occupation">keep a book-shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-170-victim1418 t18300527-170-viclabel918"></join> in <placeName id="t18300527-170-crimeloc919">Holborn</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-170-crimeloc919" type="placeName" value="Holborn"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-170-crimeloc919" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-170-off916 t18300527-170-crimeloc919"></join>. I had some books in a tray at my window - I received information, and went in pursuit of the prisoner, who was then about one hundred yards from my shop, and took this book from his breeches pocket - I had seen it safe a few minutes before.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I was walking leisurely along with this book, which I got two days befofre, in exchange for a pair of old<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183005270081"></xptr>shoes. Witness. It is my own binding, and I know it by that.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-170-person1420">
                  NICHOLAS 
                  MERRY
               <interp inst="t18300527-170-person1420" type="surname" value="MERRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-170-person1420" type="given" value="NICHOLAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-170-person1420" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was going along, and saw the prisoner put his hand up and take the book from inside the window; he put it into his breeches pocket, went up a court, and came down again - we went and took him with it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. He has told you a falsehood, for Mr. Wilton stopped me, and he was behind. Witness. No, I stopped him.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I deal in old shoes, and took the book in exchange for a pair; I wanted the Messiah for it, I went to the tray, and there was not one - I looked at his books, but it was not there; I then went down a court, and returned - the prosecutor came and said, "You have a book of mine;" I said, "You flurry me - I have nothing of yours; I have this book, which is my own."</p>
               <p>MR. WILTON. He said he was a poor man, when I stopped him.</p>
